## Task 3 — Why SIEM?

*(Reading task — no answer.)*

The five core SIEM features, each mapped to a problem from Task 2:

| Feature | What it does | Problem solved |
|---------|-------------|----------------|
| **Centralised Log Collection** | Pulls logs from all sources via agents/APIs into one place | No centralisation |
| **Normalisation** | **Parsing** = break a raw log into fields; **Normalisation** = convert all logs to one consistent format | Format issues |
| **Correlation** | Links events across sources to expose a pattern | Limited context |
| **Real-time Alerting** | Detection rules fire alerts; analysts can write custom rules | Limited analysis |
| **Dashboards & Reporting** | Normalised data shown as actionable insights | Volume / visibility |

> **Key terms:** *Parsing vs Normalisation* — classic SOC interview question.

**Correlation example:** Haris logs in via VPN from a never-seen IP → accesses a shared drive → runs a PowerShell script → outbound connection. Harmless individually; correlated, it points to **data exfiltration via compromised VPN credentials**.

